18Jb 12:12 Wisdom belongs to the aged, and understanding to the old.
18Jb 12:13 "But true wisdom and power are found in God; counsel and understanding are his.
18Jb 12:14 What he destroys cannot be rebuilt.When he puts someone in prison, there is no escape.
18Jb 12:15 If he holds back the rain, the earth becomes a desert.If he releases the waters, they flood the earth.
18Jb 12:16 Yes, strength and wisdom are his; deceivers and deceived are both in his power.
18Jb 12:17 He leads counselors away, stripped of good judgment; wise judges become fools.
18Jb 12:18 He removes the royal robe of kings.They are led away with ropes around their waist.
18Jb 12:19 He leads priests away, stripped of status; he overthrows those with long years in power.
18Jb 12:20 He silences the trusted adviser and removes the insight of the elders.
18Jb 12:21 He pours disgrace upon princes and disarms the strong.
18Jb 12:22 "He uncovers mysteries hidden in darkness; he brings light to the deepest gloom.
18Jb 12:23 He builds up nations, and he destroys them.He expands nations, and he abandons them.
18Jb 12:24 He strips kings of understanding and leaves them wandering in a pathless wasteland.
18Jb 12:25 They grope in the darkness without a light.He makes them stagger like drunkards.
18Jb 13:1 "Look, I have seen all this with my own eyes and heard it with my own ears, and now I understand.
18Jb 13:2 I know as much as you do.You are no better than I am.
18Jb 13:3 As for me, I would speak directly to the Almighty.I want to argue my case with God himself.
18Jb 13:4 As for you, you smear me with lies.As physicians, you are worthless quacks.
18Jb 13:5 If only you could be silent! That's the wisest thing you could do.
18Jb 13:6 Listen to my charge; pay attention to my arguments.
18Jb 13:7 "Are you defending God with lies? Do you make your dishonest arguments for his sake?
18Jb 13:8 Will you slant your testimony in his favor? Will you argue God's case for him?
18Jb 13:9 What will happen when he finds out what you are doing? Can you fool him as easily as you fool people?
18Jb 13:10 No, you will be in trouble with him if you secretly slant your testimony in his favor.
18Jb 13:11 Doesn't his majesty terrify you? Doesn't your fear of him overwhelm you?
18Jb 13:12 Your platitudes are as valuable as ashes.Your defense is as fragile as a clay pot.
18Jb 13:13 "Be silent now and leave me alone.Let me speak, and I will face the consequences.
18Jb 13:14 Yes, I will take my life in my hands and say what I really think.
18Jb 13:15 God might kill me, but I have no other hope®Á. I am going to argue my case with him. / ®ÁAn alternate reading in the Masoretic Text reads God might kill me, but I hope in him
18Jb 13:16 But this is what will save me - I am not godless.If I were, I could not stand before him.
18Jb 13:17 "Listen closely to what I am about to say.Hear me out.
18Jb 13:18 I have prepared my case; I will be proved innocent.
18Jb 13:19 Who can argue with me over this? And if you prove me wrong, I will remain silent and die.
18Jb 13:20 "O God, grant me these two things, and then I will be able to face you.
18Jb 13:21 Remove your heavy hand from me, and don't terrify me with your awesome presence.
18Jb 13:22 Now summon me, and I will answer! Or let me speak to you, and you reply.
18Jb 13:23 Tell me, what have I done wrong? Show me my rebellion and my sin.
18Jb 13:24 Why do you turn away from me? Why do you treat me as your enemy?
18Jb 13:25 Would you terrify a leaf blown by the wind? Would you chase dry straw?
18Jb 13:26 "You write bitter accusations against me and bring up all the sins of my youth.
18Jb 13:27 You put my feet in stocks.You examine all my paths.You trace all my footprints.
18Jb 13:28 I waste away like rotting wood, like a moth-eaten coat.
18Jb 14:1 "How frail is humanity! How short is life, how full of trouble!
18Jb 14:2 We blossom like a flower and then wither.Like a passing shadow, we quickly disappear.
18Jb 14:3 Must you keep an eye on such a frail creature and demand an accounting from me?
18Jb 14:4 Who can bring purity out of an impure person? No one!
18Jb 14:5 You have decided the length of our lives.You know how many months we will live, and we are not given a minute longer.
18Jb 14:6 So leave us alone and let us rest! We are like hired hands, so let us finish our work in peace.
18Jb 14:7 "Even a tree has more hope! If it is cut down, it will sprout again and grow new branches.
18Jb 14:8 Though its roots have grown old in the earth and its stump decays,
18Jb 14:9 at the scent of water it will bud and sprout again like a new seedling.
18Jb 14:10 "But when people die, their strength is gone.They breathe their last, and then where are they?
18Jb 14:11 As water evaporates from a lake and a river disappears in drought,
18Jb 14:12 people are laid to rest and do not rise again.Until the heavens are no more, they will not wake up nor be roused from their sleep.
18Jb 14:13 "I wish you would hide me in the grave®Á and forget me there until your anger has passed.But mark your calendar to think of me again! / ®ÁHebrew in Sheol
18Jb 14:14 Can the dead live again? If so, this would give me hope through all my years of struggle, and I would eagerly await the release of death.
18Jb 14:15 You would call and I would answer, and you would yearn for me, your handiwork.
18Jb 14:16 For then you would guard my steps, instead of watching for my sins.
18Jb 14:17 My sins would be sealed in a pouch, and you would cover my guilt.
18Jb 14:18 "But instead, as mountains fall and crumble and as rocks fall from a cliff,
18Jb 14:19 as water wears away the stones and floods wash away the soil, so you destroy people's hope.
18Jb 14:20 You always overpower them, and they pass from the scene.You disfigure them in death and send them away.
18Jb 14:21 They never know if their children grow up in honor or sink to insignificance.
18Jb 14:22 They suffer painfully; their life is full of trouble."
18Jb 15:1 Then Eliphaz the Temanite replied.
18Jb 15:2 "A wise man wouldn't answer with such empty talk! You are nothing but a windbag.
18Jb 15:3 The wise don't engage in empty chatter.What good are such words?
18Jb 15:4 Have you no fear of God, no reverence for him?
18Jb 15:5 Your sins are telling your mouth what to say.Your words are based on clever deception.
18Jb 15:6 Your own mouth condemns you, not I.Your own lips testify against you.
18Jb 15:7 "Were you the first person ever born? Were you born before the hills were made?
18Jb 15:8 Were you listening at God's secret council? Do you have a monopoly on wisdom?
18Jb 15:9 What do you know that we don't? What do you understand that we do not?
18Jb 15:10 On our side are aged, gray-haired men much older than your father!
18Jb 15:11 "Is God's comfort too little for you? Is his gentle word not enough?
18Jb 15:12 What has taken away your reason? What has weakened your vision®Á, / ®ÁOr Why do your eyes flash with anger; Hebrew reads Why do your eyes blink
18Jb 15:13 that you turn against God and say all these evil things?
18Jb 15:14 Can any mortal be pure? Can anyone born of a woman be just?
18Jb 15:15 Look, God does not even trust the angels®Á. Even the heavens are not absolutely pure in his sight. / ®ÁHebrew the holy ones
18Jb 15:16 How much less pure is a corrupt and sinful person with a thirst for wickedness!
18Jb 15:17 "If you will listen, I will show you.I will answer you from my own experience.
18Jb 15:18 And it is confirmed by the reports of wise men who have heard the same thing from their fathers - 
18Jb 15:19 from those to whom the land was given long before any foreigners arrived.
18Jb 15:20 "The wicked writhe in pain throughout their lives.Years of trouble are stored up for the ruthless.
18Jb 15:21 The sound of terror rings in their ears, and even on good days they fear the attack of the destroyer.
18Jb 15:22 They dare not go out into the darkness for fear they will be murdered.
18Jb 15:23 They wander around, saying, 'Where can I find bread?'®Á They know their day of destruction is near. / ®ÁGreek version reads He is appointed to be food for a vulture
18Jb 15:24 That dark day terrifies them.They live in distress and anguish, like a king preparing for battle.
18Jb 15:25 For they shake their fists at God, defying the Almighty.
18Jb 15:26 Holding their strong shields, they defiantly charge against him.
18Jb 15:27 "These wicked people are heavy and prosperous; their waists bulge with fat.
18Jb 15:28 But their cities will be ruined.They will live in abandoned houses that are ready to tumble down.
18Jb 15:29 Their riches will not last, and their wealth will not endure.Their possessions will no longer spread across the horizon.
18Jb 15:30 "They will not escape the darkness.The burning sun will wither their shoots, and the breath of God will destroy them.
18Jb 15:31 Let them no longer fool themselves by trusting in empty riches, for emptiness will be their only reward.
18Jb 15:32 Like trees, they will be cut down in the prime of life; their branches will never again be green.
18Jb 15:33 They will be like a vine whose grapes are harvested too early, like an olive tree that loses its blossoms before the fruit can form.
18Jb 15:34 For the godless are barren.Their homes, enriched through bribery, will burn.
18Jb 15:35 They conceive trouble and give birth to evil.Their womb produces deceit."
18Jb 16:1 Then Job spoke again.
18Jb 16:2 "I have heard all this before.What miserable comforters you are!
18Jb 16:3 Won't you ever stop blowing hot air? What makes you keep on talking?
18Jb 16:4 I could say the same things if you were in my place.I could spout off criticism and shake my head at you.
18Jb 16:5 But if it were me, I would encourage you.I would try to take away your grief.
18Jb 16:6 Instead, I suffer if I defend myself, and I suffer no less if I refuse to speak.
18Jb 16:7 "O God, you have ground me down and devastated my family.
18Jb 16:8 As if to prove I have sinned, you've reduced me to skin and bones.My gaunt flesh testifies against me.
18Jb 16:9 God hates me and angrily tears me apart.He snaps his teeth at me and pierces me with his eyes.
18Jb 16:10 People jeer and laugh at me.They slap my cheek in contempt.A mob gathers against me.
18Jb 16:11 God has handed me over to sinners.He has tossed me into the hands of the wicked.
18Jb 16:12 "I was living quietly until he shattered me.He took me by the neck and broke me in pieces. Then he set me up as his target,
18Jb 16:13 and now his archers surround me.His arrows pierce me without mercy.The ground is wet with my blood®Á. / ®ÁHebrew my gall
18Jb 16:14 Again and again he smashes against me, charging at me like a warrior.
18Jb 16:15 I wear burlap to show my grief.My pride lies in the dust.
18Jb 16:16 My eyes are red with weeping; dark shadows circle my eyes.
18Jb 16:17 Yet I have done no wrong, and my prayer is pure.
18Jb 16:18 "O earth, do not conceal my blood.Let it cry out on my behalf.
18Jb 16:19 Even now my witness is in heaven.My advocate is there on high.
18Jb 16:20 My friends scorn me, but I pour out my tears to God.
18Jb 16:21 I need someone to mediate between God and me, as a person mediates between friends.
18Jb 16:22 For soon I must go down that road from which I will never return.
18Jb 17:1 "My spirit is crushed, and my life is nearly snuffed out.The grave is ready to receive me.
18Jb 17:2 I am surrounded by mockers.I watch how bitterly they taunt me.
18Jb 17:3 "You must defend my innocence, O God, since no one else will stand up for me.
18Jb 17:4 You have closed their minds to understanding, but do not let them triumph.
18Jb 17:5 They betray their friends for their own advantage, so let their children faint with hunger.
18Jb 17:6 "God has made a mockery of me among the people; they spit in my face.
18Jb 17:7 My eyes are swollen with weeping, and I am but a shadow of my former self.
18Jb 17:8 The virtuous are horrified when they see me.The innocent rise up against the ungodly.
18Jb 17:9 The righteous keep moving forward, and those with clean hands become stronger and stronger.
18Jb 17:10 "As for all of you, come back with a better argument, though I still won't find a wise man among you.
18Jb 17:11 My days are over.My hopes have disappeared.My heart's desires are broken.
18Jb 17:12 These men say that night is day; they claim that the darkness is light.
18Jb 17:13 What if I go to the grave®Á and make my bed in darkness? / ®ÁHebrew to Sheol; also in 17.16
18Jb 17:14 What if I call the grave my father, and the maggot my mother or my sister?
18Jb 17:15 Where then is my hope? Can anyone find it?
18Jb 17:16 No, my hope will go down with me to the grave.We will rest together in the dust!"
18Jb 18:1 Then Bildad the Shuhite replied.
18Jb 18:2 "How long before you stop talking? Speak sense if you want us to answer!
18Jb 18:3 Do you think we are mere animals? Do you think we are stupid?
18Jb 18:4 You may tear out your hair in anger, but will that destroy the earth? Will it make the rocks tremble?
18Jb 18:5 "Surely the light of the wicked will be snuffed out.The sparks of their fire will not glow.
18Jb 18:6 The light in their tent will grow dark.The lamp hanging above them will be quenched.
18Jb 18:7 The confident stride of the wicked will be shortened.Their own schemes will be their downfall.
18Jb 18:8 The wicked walk into a net.They fall into a pit.
18Jb 18:9 A trap grabs them by the heel.A snare holds them tight.
18Jb 18:10 A noose lies hidden on the ground.A rope is stretched across their path.
18Jb 18:11 "Terrors surround the wicked and trouble them at every step.
18Jb 18:12 Hunger depletes their strength, and calamity waits for them to stumble.
18Jb 18:13 Disease eats their skin; death devours their limbs.
18Jb 18:14 They are torn from the security of their homes and are brought down to the king of terrors.
18Jb 18:15 The homes of the wicked will burn down; burning sulfur rains on their houses.
18Jb 18:16 Their roots will dry up, and their branches will wither.
18Jb 18:17 All memory of their existence will fade from the earth, No one will remember their names.
18Jb 18:18 They will be thrust from light into darkness, driven from the world.
18Jb 18:19 They will have neither children nor grandchildren, nor any survivor in the place where they lived.
18Jb 18:20 People in the west are appalled at their fate; people in the east are horrified.
18Jb 18:21 They will say, 'This was the home of a wicked person, the place of one who rejected God.'"
18Jb 19:1 Then Job spoke again.
18Jb 19:2 "How long will you torture me? How long will you try to crush me with your words?
18Jb 19:3 You have already insulted me ten times.You should be ashamed of treating me so badly.
18Jb 19:4 Even if I have sinned, that is my concern, not yours.
18Jb 19:5 You think you're better than I am, using my humiliation as evidence of my sin.
18Jb 19:6 But it is God who has wronged me, capturing me in his net®Á. / ®ÁOr for I am like a city under siege
18Jb 19:7 "I cry out, 'Help!' but no one answers me.I protest, but there is no justice.
18Jb 19:8 God has blocked my way so I cannot move.He has plunged my path into darkness.
18Jb 19:9 He has stripped me of my honor and removed the crown from my head.
18Jb 19:10 He has demolished me on every side, and I am finished.He has uprooted my hope like a fallen tree.
18Jb 19:11 His fury burns against me; he counts me as an enemy.
18Jb 19:12 His troops advance.They build up roads to attack me.They camp all around my tent.
18Jb 19:13 "My relatives stay far away, and my friends have turned against me.
18Jb 19:14 My family is gone, and my close friends have forgotten me.
18Jb 19:15 My servants and maids consider me a stranger.I am like a foreigner to them.
18Jb 19:16 When I call my servant, he doesn't come; I have to plead with him!
18Jb 19:17 My breath is repulsive to my wife.I am rejected by my own family.
18Jb 19:18 Even young children despise me.When I stand to speak, they turn their backs on me.
18Jb 19:19 My close friends detest me.Those I loved have turned against me.
18Jb 19:20 I have been reduced to skin and bones and have escaped death by the skin of my teeth.
18Jb 19:21 "Have mercy on me, my friends, have mercy, for the hand of God has struck me.
18Jb 19:22 Must you also persecute me, like God does? Haven't you chewed me up enough?
18Jb 19:23 "Oh, that my words could be recorded.Oh, that they could be inscribed on a monument,
18Jb 19:24 carved with an iron chisel and filled with lead, engraved forever in the rock.
18Jb 19:25 "But as for me, I know that my Redeemer lives, and he will stand upon the earth at last.
18Jb 19:26 And after my body has decayed, yet in my body I will see God!®Á / ®ÁOr without my body I will see God! The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain
18Jb 19:27 I will see him for myself.Yes, I will see him with my own eyes.I am overwhelmed at the thought!
18Jb 19:28 "How dare you go on persecuting me, saying, 'It's his own fault'?
18Jb 19:29 You should fear punishment yourselves, for your attitude deserves punishment.Then you will know that there is indeed a judgment."
18Jb 20:1 Then Zophar the Naamathite replied.
18Jb 20:2 "I must reply because I am greatly disturbed.
18Jb 20:3 I've had to endure your insults, but now my spirit prompts me to reply.
18Jb 20:4 "Don't you realize that from the beginning of time, ever since people were first placed on the earth,
18Jb 20:5 the triumph of the wicked has been short lived and the joy of the godless has been only temporary?
18Jb 20:6 Though the pride of the godless reaches to the heavens and their heads touch the clouds,
18Jb 20:7 yet they will vanish forever, thrown away like their own dung.Those who knew them will ask, 'Where are they?'
18Jb 20:8 They will fade like a dream and not be found.They will vanish like a vision in the night.
18Jb 20:9 Those who once saw them will see them no more.Their families will never see them again.
18Jb 20:10 Their children will beg from the poor, for they must give back their stolen riches.
18Jb 20:11 Though they are young, their bones will lie in the dust.
18Jb 20:12 "They enjoyed the sweet taste of wickedness, letting it melt under their tongue.
18Jb 20:13 They savored it, holding it long in their mouths.
18Jb 20:14 But suddenly the food in their bellies turns sour, a poisonous venom in their stomach.
18Jb 20:15 They will vomit the wealth they swallowed.God won't let them keep it down.
18Jb 20:16 They will suck the poison of cobras.The viper will kill them.
18Jb 20:17 They will never again enjoy streams of olive oil or rivers of milk and honey.
18Jb 20:18 They will give back everything they worked for.Their wealth will bring them no joy.
18Jb 20:19 For they oppressed the poor and left them destitute.They foreclosed on their homes.
18Jb 20:20 They were always greedy and never satisfied.Nothing remains of all the things they dreamed about.
18Jb 20:21 Nothing is left after they finish gorging themselves.Therefore, their prosperity will not endure.
18Jb 20:22 "In the midst of plenty, they will run into trouble and be overcome by misery.
18Jb 20:23 May God give them a bellyful of trouble.May God rain down his anger upon them.
18Jb 20:24 When they try to escape an iron weapon, a bronze-tipped arrow will pierce them.
18Jb 20:25 The arrow is pulled from their back, and the arrowhead glistens with blood®Á. The terrors of death are upon them. / ®ÁHebrew with gall
18Jb 20:26 Their treasures will be thrown into deepest darkness. A wildfire will devour their goods, consuming all they have left.
18Jb 20:27 The heavens will reveal their guilt, and the earth will testify against them.
18Jb 20:28 A flood will sweep away their house.God's anger will descend on them in torrents.
18Jb 20:29 This is the reward that God gives the wicked.It is the inheritance decreed by God."
18Jb 21:1 Then Job spoke again.
18Jb 21:2 "Listen closely to what I am saying.That's one consolation you can give me.
18Jb 21:3 Bear with me, and let me speak.After I have spoken, you may resume mocking me.
18Jb 21:4 "My complaint is with God, not with people.I have good reason to be so impatient.
18Jb 21:5 Look at me and be stunned.Put your hand over your mouth in shock.
18Jb 21:6 When I think about what I am saying, I shudder.My body trembles.
18Jb 21:7 "Why do the wicked prosper, growing old and powerful?
18Jb 21:8 They live to see their children grow up and settle down, and they enjoy their grandchildren.
18Jb 21:9 Their homes are safe from every fear, and God does not punish them.
18Jb 21:10 Their bulls never fail to breed.Their cows bear calves and never miscarry.
18Jb 21:11 They let their children frisk about like lambs.Their little ones skip and dance.
18Jb 21:12 They sing with tambourine and harp.They celebrate to the sound of the flute.
18Jb 21:13 They spend their days in prosperity, then go down to the grave®Á in peace. / ®ÁHebrew to Sheol
18Jb 21:14 And yet they say to God, 'Go away.We want no part of you and your ways.
18Jb 21:15 Who is the Almighty, and why should we obey him? What good will it do us to pray?'
18Jb 21:16 (They think their prosperity is of their own doing, but I will have nothing to do with that kind of thinking.)
18Jb 21:17 "Yet the light of the wicked never seems to be extinguished.Do they ever have trouble? Does God distribute sorrows to them in anger?
18Jb 21:18 Are they driven before the wind like straw? Are they carried away by the storm like chaff? Not at all!
18Jb 21:19 "'Well,' you say, 'at least God will punish their children!' But I say he should punish the ones who sin, so that they understand his judgment.
18Jb 21:20 Let them see their destruction with their own eyes.Let them drink deeply of the anger of the Almighty.
18Jb 21:21 For they will not care what happens to their family after they are dead.
18Jb 21:22 "But who can teach a lesson to God, since he judges even the most powerful?
18Jb 21:23 One person dies in prosperity, completely comfortable and secure,
18Jb 21:24 the picture of good health, vigorous and fit.
18Jb 21:25 Another person dies in bitter poverty, never having tasted the good life.
18Jb 21:26 But both are buried in the same dust, both eaten by the same maggots.
18Jb 21:27 "Look, I know what you're thinking.I know the schemes you plot against me.
18Jb 21:28 You will tell me of rich and wicked people whose houses have vanished because of their sins.
18Jb 21:29 But ask those who have been around, and they will tell you the truth.
18Jb 21:30 Evil people are spared in times of calamity and are allowed to escape disaster.
18Jb 21:31 No one criticizes them openly or pays them back for what they have done.
18Jb 21:32 When they are carried to the grave, an honor guard keeps watch at their tomb.
18Jb 21:33 A great funeral procession goes to the cemetery.Many pay their respects as the body is laid to rest, and the earth gives sweet repose.
18Jb 21:34 "How can your empty cliches comfort me? All your explanations are lies!"
18Jb 22:1 Then Eliphaz the Temanite replied.
18Jb 22:2 "Can a person do anything to help God? Can even a wise person be helpful to him?
18Jb 22:3 Is it any advantage to the Almighty if you are righteous? Would it be any gain to him if you were perfect?
18Jb 22:4 Is it because you're so pious that he accuses you and brings judgment against you?
18Jb 22:5 No, it's because of your wickedness! There's no limit to your sins.
18Jb 22:6 "For example, you must have lent money to your friend and demanded clothing as security.Yes, you stripped him to the bone.
18Jb 22:7 You must have refused water for the thirsty and food for the hungry.
18Jb 22:8 You probably think the land belongs to the powerful and only the privileged have a right to it!
18Jb 22:9 You must have sent widows away empty-handed and crushed the hopes of orphans.
18Jb 22:10 That is why you are surrounded by traps and tremble from sudden fears.
18Jb 22:11 That is why you cannot see in the darkness, and waves of water cover you.
18Jb 22:12 "God is so great - higher than the heavens, higher than the farthest stars.
18Jb 22:13 But you reply, 'That's why God can't see what I am doing! How can he judge through the thick darkness?
18Jb 22:14 For thick clouds swirl about him, and he cannot see us.He is way up there, walking on the vault of heaven.'
18Jb 22:15 "Will you continue on the old paths where evil people have walked?
18Jb 22:16 They were snatched away in the prime of life, the foundations of their lives washed away.
18Jb 22:17 For they said to God, 'Leave us alone! What can the Almighty do to us?'
18Jb 22:18 Yet he was the one who filled their homes with good things, so I will have nothing to do with that kind of thinking.
18Jb 22:19 "The righteous will be happy to see the wicked destroyed, and the innocent will laugh in contempt.
18Jb 22:20 They will say, 'See how our enemies have been destroyed.The last of them have been consumed in the fire.'
18Jb 22:21 "Submit to God, and you will have peace; then things will go well for you.
18Jb 22:22 Listen to his instructions, and store them in your heart.
18Jb 22:23 If you return to the Almighty, you will be restored - so clean up your life.
18Jb 22:24 If you give up your lust for money and throw your precious gold into the river,
18Jb 22:25 the Almighty himself will be your treasure.He will be your precious silver!
18Jb 22:26 "Then you will take delight in the Almighty and look up to God.
18Jb 22:27 You will pray to him, and he will hear you, and you will fulfill your vows to him.
18Jb 22:28 You will succeed in whatever you choose to do, and light will shine on the road ahead of you.
18Jb 22:29 If people are in trouble and you say, 'Help them,' God will save them.
18Jb 22:30 Even sinners will be rescued; they will be rescued because your hands are pure."
18Jb 23:1 Then Job spoke again.
18Jb 23:2 "My complaint today is still a bitter one, and I try hard not to groan aloud.
18Jb 23:3 If only I knew where to find God, I would go to his court.
18Jb 23:4 I would lay out my case and present my arguments.
18Jb 23:5 Then I would listen to his reply and understand what he says to me.
18Jb 23:6 Would he use his great power to argue with me? No, he would give me a fair hearing.
18Jb 23:7 Honest people can reason with him, so I would be forever acquitted by my judge.
18Jb 23:8 I go east, but he is not there.I go west, but I cannot find him.
18Jb 23:9 I do not see him in the north, for he is hidden.I look to the south, but he is concealed.
18Jb 23:10 "But he knows where I am going.And when he tests me, I will come out as pure as gold.
18Jb 23:11 For I have stayed on God's paths; I have followed his ways and not turned aside.
18Jb 23:12 I have not departed from his commands, but have treasured his words more than daily food.
18Jb 23:13 But once he has made his decision, who can change his mind? Whatever he wants to do, he does.
18Jb 23:14 So he will do to me whatever he has planned.He controls my destiny.
18Jb 23:15 No wonder I am so terrified in his presence.When I think of it, terror grips me.
18Jb 23:16 God has made me sick at heart; the Almighty has terrified me.
18Jb 23:17 Darkness is all around me; thick, impenetrable darkness is everywhere.
18Jb 24:1 "Why doesn't the Almighty bring the wicked to judgment? Why must the godly wait for him in vain?
18Jb 24:2 Evil people steal land by moving the boundary markers.They steal livestock and put them in their own pastures.
18Jb 24:3 They take the orphan's donkey and demand the widow's ox as security for a loan.
18Jb 24:4 The poor are pushed off the path; the needy must hide together for safety.
18Jb 24:5 Like wild donkeys in the wilderness, the poor must spend all their time looking for food, searching even in the desert for food for their children.
18Jb 24:6 They harvest a field they do not own, and they glean in the vineyards of the wicked.
18Jb 24:7 All night they lie naked in the cold, without clothing or covering.
18Jb 24:8 They are soaked by mountain showers, and they huddle against the rocks for want of a home.
18Jb 24:9 "The wicked snatch a widow's child from her breast, taking the baby as security for a loan.
18Jb 24:10 The poor must go about naked, without any clothing.They harvest food for others while they themselves are starving.
18Jb 24:11 They press out olive oil without being allowed to taste it, and they tread in the winepress as they suffer from thirst.
18Jb 24:12 The groans of the dying rise from the city, and the wounded cry for help, yet God ignores their moaning.
18Jb 24:13 "Wicked people rebel against the light.They refuse to acknowledge its ways or stay in its paths.
18Jb 24:14 The murderer rises in the early dawn to kill the poor and needy; at night he is a thief.
18Jb 24:15 The adulterer waits for the twilight, saying, 'No one will see me then.' He hides his face so no one will know him.
18Jb 24:16 Thieves break into houses at night and sleep in the daytime.They are not acquainted with the light.
18Jb 24:17 The black night is their morning.They ally themselves with the terrors of the darkness.
18Jb 24:18 "But they disappear like foam down a river.Everything they own is cursed, and they are afraid to enter their own vineyards.
18Jb 24:19 The grave®Á consumes sinners just as drought and heat consume snow. / ®ÁHebrew Sheol
18Jb 24:20 Their own mothers will forget them.Maggots will find them sweet to eat. No one will remember them.Wicked people are broken like a tree in the storm.
18Jb 24:21 They cheat the woman who has no son to help her.They refuse to help the needy widow.
18Jb 24:22 "God, in his power, drags away the rich.They may rise high, but they have no assurance of life.
18Jb 24:23 They may be allowed to live in security, but God is always watching them.
18Jb 24:24 And though they are great now, in a moment they will be gone like all others, cut off like heads of grain.
18Jb 24:25 Can anyone claim otherwise? Who can prove me wrong?"
18Jb 25:1 Then Bildad the Shuhite replied.
18Jb 25:2 "God is powerful and dreadful.He enforces peace in the heavens.
18Jb 25:3 Who is able to count his heavenly army? Doesn't his light shine on all the earth?
18Jb 25:4 How can a mortal be innocent before God? Can anyone born of a woman be pure?
18Jb 25:5 God is more glorious than the moon; he shines brighter than the stars.
18Jb 25:6 In comparison, people are maggots; we mortals are mere worms."
18Jb 26:1 Then Job spoke again.
18Jb 26:2 "How you have helped the powerless! How you have saved the weak!
18Jb 26:3 How you have enlightened my stupidity! What wise advice you have offered!
18Jb 26:4 Where have you gotten all these wise sayings? Whose spirit speaks through you?
18Jb 26:5 "The dead tremble - those who live beneath the waters.
18Jb 26:6 The underworld®Á is naked in God's presence.The place of destruction®Ë is uncovered. / ®ÁHebrew Sheol. ®ËHebrew Abaddon
18Jb 26:7 God stretches the northern sky over empty space and hangs the earth on nothing.
18Jb 26:8 He wraps the rain in his thick clouds, and the clouds don't burst with the weight.
18Jb 26:9 He covers the face of the moon®Á, shrouding it with his clouds. / ®ÁOr covers his throne
18Jb 26:10 He created the horizon when he separated the waters; he set the boundary between day and night.
18Jb 26:11 The foundations of heaven tremble; they shudder at his rebuke.
18Jb 26:12 By his power the sea grew calm.By his skill he crushed the great sea monster®Á. / ®ÁHebrew Rahab, the name of a mythical sea monster that represents chaos in ancient literature
18Jb 26:13 His Spirit made the heavens beautiful, and his power pierced the gliding serpent.
18Jb 26:14 These are just the beginning of all that he does, merely a whisper of his power.Who, then, can comprehend the thunder of his power?"
18Jb 27:1 Job continued speaking.
18Jb 27:2 "I vow by the living God, who has taken away my rights, by the Almighty who has embittered my soul - 
18Jb 27:3 As long as I live, while I have breath from God,
18Jb 27:4 my lips will speak no evil, and my tongue will speak no lies.
18Jb 27:5 I will never concede that you are right; I will defend my integrity until I die.
18Jb 27:6 I will maintain my innocence without wavering.My conscience is clear for as long as I live.
18Jb 27:7 "May my enemy be punished like the wicked, my adversary like those who do evil.
18Jb 27:8 For what hope do the godless have when God cuts them off and takes away their life?
18Jb 27:9 Will God listen to their cry when trouble comes upon them?
18Jb 27:10 Can they take delight in the Almighty? Can they call to God at any time?
18Jb 27:11 I will teach you about God's power.I will not conceal anything concerning the Almighty.
18Jb 27:12 But you have seen all this, yet you say all these useless things to me.
18Jb 27:13 "This is what the wicked will receive from God; this is their inheritance from the Almighty.
18Jb 27:14 They may have many children, but the children will die in war or starve to death.
18Jb 27:15 Those who survive will die of a plague, and not even their widows will mourn them.
18Jb 27:16 "Evil people may have piles of money and may store away mounds of clothing.
18Jb 27:17 But the righteous will wear that clothing, and the innocent will divide that money.
18Jb 27:18 The wicked build houses as fragile as a spider's web®Á, as flimsy as a shelter made of branches. / ®ÁAs in Greek and Syriac versions (see also 8.14); Hebrew reads a moth
18Jb 27:19 The wicked go to bed rich but wake to find that all their wealth is gone.
18Jb 27:20 Terror overwhelms them like a flood, and they are blown away in the storms of the night.
18Jb 27:21 The east wind carries them away, and they are gone.It sweeps them away.
18Jb 27:22 It whirls down on them without mercy.They struggle to flee from its power.
18Jb 27:23 But everyone jeers at them and mocks them.
18Jb 28:1 "People know where to mine silver and how to refine gold.
18Jb 28:2 They know where to dig iron from the earth and how to smelt copper from rock.
18Jb 28:3 They know how to shine light in the darkness and explore the farthest regions of the earth as they search in the dark for ore.
18Jb 28:4 They sink a mine shaft into the earth far from where anyone lives.They descend on ropes, swinging back and forth.
18Jb 28:5 Food is grown on the earth above, but down below, the earth is melted as by fire.
18Jb 28:6 Here the rocks contain precious lapis lazuli, and the dust contains gold.
18Jb 28:7 These are treasures no bird of prey can see, no falcon's eye observe.
18Jb 28:8 No wild animal has walked upon these treasures; no lion has ever set his paw there.
18Jb 28:9 People know how to tear apart flinty rocks and overturn the roots of mountains.
18Jb 28:10 They cut tunnels in the rocks and uncover precious stones.
18Jb 28:11 They dam up the trickling streams and bring to light the hidden treasures.
18Jb 28:12 "But do people know where to find wisdom? Where can they find understanding?
18Jb 28:13 No one knows where to find it, for it is not found among the living.
18Jb 28:14 'It is not here,' says the ocean.'Nor is it here,' says the sea.
18Jb 28:15 It cannot be bought with gold.It cannot be purchased with silver.
18Jb 28:16 It's worth more than all the gold of Ophir, greater than precious onyx or lapis lazuli.
18Jb 28:17 Wisdom is more valuable than gold and crystal.It cannot be purchased with jewels mounted in fine gold.
18Jb 28:18 Coral and jasper are worthless in trying to get it.The price of wisdom is far above rubies.
18Jb 28:19 Precious peridot from Ethiopia®Á cannot be exchanged for it.It's worth more than the purest gold. / ®ÁHebrew from Cush
18Jb 28:20 "But do people know where to find wisdom? Where can they find understanding?
18Jb 28:21 It is hidden from the eyes of all humanity.Even the sharp-eyed birds in the sky cannot discover it.
18Jb 28:22 Destruction®Á and Death say, 'We've heard only rumors of where wisdom can be found.' / ®ÁHebrew Abaddon
18Jb 28:23 "God alone understands the way to wisdom; he knows where it can be found,
18Jb 28:24 for he looks throughout the whole earth and sees everything under the heavens.
18Jb 28:25 He decided how hard the winds should blow and how much rain should fall.
18Jb 28:26 He made the laws for the rain and laid out a path for the lightning.
18Jb 28:27 Then he saw wisdom and evaluated it.He set it in place and examined it thoroughly.
18Jb 28:28 And this is what he says to all humanity£∫ 'The fear of the Lord is true wisdom; to forsake evil is real understanding.'"
18Jb 29:1 Job continued speaking.
18Jb 29:2 "I long for the years gone by when God took care of me,
18Jb 29:3 when he lit up the way before me and I walked safely through the darkness.
18Jb 29:4 When I was in my prime, God's friendship was felt in my home.
18Jb 29:5 The Almighty was still with me, and my children were around me.
18Jb 29:6 My cows produced milk in abundance, and my groves poured out streams of olive oil.
18Jb 29:7 "Those were the days when I went to the city gate and took my place among the honored leaders.
18Jb 29:8 The young stepped aside when they saw me, and even the aged rose in respect at my coming.
18Jb 29:9 The princes stood in silence and put their hands over their mouths.
18Jb 29:10 The highest officials of the city stood quietly, holding their tongues in respect.
18Jb 29:11 "All who heard me praised me.All who saw me spoke well of me.
18Jb 29:12 For I assisted the poor in their need and the orphans who required help.
18Jb 29:13 I helped those without hope, and they blessed me.And I caused the widows' hearts to sing for joy.
18Jb 29:14 Everything I did was honest.Righteousness covered me like a robe, and I wore justice like a turban.
18Jb 29:15 I served as eyes for the blind and feet for the lame.
18Jb 29:16 I was a father to the poor and assisted strangers who needed help.
18Jb 29:17 I broke the jaws of godless oppressors and plucked their victims from their teeth.
18Jb 29:18 "I thought, 'Surely I will die surrounded by my family after a long, good life®Á. / ®ÁHebrew after I have counted my days like sand
18Jb 29:19 For I am like a tree whose roots reach the water, whose branches are refreshed with the dew.
18Jb 29:20 New honors are constantly bestowed on me, and my strength is continually renewed.'
18Jb 29:21 "Everyone listened to my advice.They were silent as they waited for me to speak.
18Jb 29:22 And after I spoke, they had nothing to add, for my counsel satisfied them.
18Jb 29:23 They longed for me to speak as people long for rain.They drank my words like a refreshing spring rain.
18Jb 29:24 When they were discouraged, I smiled at them.My look of approval was precious to them.
18Jb 29:25 Like a chief, I told them what to do.I lived like a king among his troops and comforted those who mourned.
18Jb 30:1 "But now I am mocked by people younger than I, by young men whose fathers are not worthy to run with my sheepdogs.
18Jb 30:2 A lot of good they are to me - those worn-out wretches!
18Jb 30:3 They are gaunt with hunger and flee to the deserts, to desolate and gloomy wastelands.
18Jb 30:4 They pluck wild greens from among the bushes and eat from the roots of broom trees.
18Jb 30:5 They are driven from human society, and people shout at them as if they were thieves.
18Jb 30:6 So now they live in frightening ravines, in caves and among the rocks.
18Jb 30:7 They sound like animals howling among the bushes, huddled together beneath the nettles.
18Jb 30:8 They are nameless fools, outcasts from society.
18Jb 30:9 "And now they mock me with vulgar songs! They taunt me!
18Jb 30:10 They despise me and won't come near me, except to spit in my face.
18Jb 30:11 For God has cut my bowstring.He has humbled me, so they have thrown off all restraint.
18Jb 30:12 These outcasts oppose me to my face.They send me sprawling and lay traps in my path.
18Jb 30:13 They block my road and do everything they can to destroy me. They know I have no one to help me.
18Jb 30:14 They come at me from all directions. They jump on me when I am down.
18Jb 30:15 I live in terror now.My honor has blown away in the wind, and my prosperity has vanished like a cloud.
18Jb 30:16 "And now my life seeps away.Depression haunts my days.
18Jb 30:17 At night my bones are filled with pain, which gnaws at me relentlessly.
18Jb 30:18 With a strong hand, God grabs my shirt.He grips me by the collar of my coat.
18Jb 30:19 He has thrown me into the mud.I'm nothing more than dust and ashes.
18Jb 30:20 "I cry to you, O God, but you don't answer.I stand before you, but you don't even look.
18Jb 30:21 You have become cruel toward me.You use your power to persecute me.
18Jb 30:22 You throw me into the whirlwind and destroy me in the storm.
18Jb 30:23 And I know you are sending me to my death - the destination of all who live.
18Jb 30:24 "Surely no one would turn against the needy when they cry for help in their trouble.
18Jb 30:25 Did I not weep for those in trouble? Was I not deeply grieved for the needy?
18Jb 30:26 So I looked for good, but evil came instead.I waited for the light, but darkness fell.
18Jb 30:27 My heart is troubled and restless.Days of suffering torment me.
18Jb 30:28 I walk in gloom, without sunlight.I stand in the public square and cry for help.
18Jb 30:29 Instead, I am considered a brother to jackals and a companion to owls.
18Jb 30:30 My skin has turned dark, and my bones burn with fever.
18Jb 30:31 My harp plays sad music, and my flute accompanies those who weep.
18Jb 31:1 "I made a covenant with my eyes not to look with lust at a young woman.
18Jb 31:2 For what has God above chosen for us? What is our inheritance from the Almighty on high?
18Jb 31:3 Isn't it calamity for the wicked and misfortune for those who do evil?
18Jb 31:4 Doesn't he see everything I do and every step I take?
18Jb 31:5 "Have I lied to anyone or deceived anyone?
18Jb 31:6 Let God weigh me on the scales of justice, for he knows my integrity.
18Jb 31:7 If I have strayed from his pathway, or if my heart has lusted for what my eyes have seen, or if I am guilty of any other sin,
18Jb 31:8 then let someone else eat the crops I have planted.Let all that I have planted be uprooted.
18Jb 31:9 "If my heart has been seduced by a woman, or if I have lusted for my neighbor's wife,
18Jb 31:10 then let my wife belong to®Á another man; let other men sleep with her. / ®ÁHebrew grind for
18Jb 31:11 For lust is a shameful sin, a crime that should be punished.
18Jb 31:12 It is a fire that burns all the way to hell®Á. It would wipe out everything I own. / ®ÁHebrew to Abaddon
18Jb 31:13 "If I have been unfair to my male or female servants when they brought their complaints to me,
18Jb 31:14 how could I face God? What could I say when he questioned me?
18Jb 31:15 For God created both me and my servants.He created us both in the womb.
18Jb 31:16 "Have I refused to help the poor, or crushed the hopes of widows?
18Jb 31:17 Have I been stingy with my food and refused to share it with orphans?
18Jb 31:18 No, from childhood I have cared for orphans like a father, and all my life I have cared for widows.
18Jb 31:19 Whenever I saw the homeless without clothes and the needy with nothing to wear,
18Jb 31:20 did they not praise me for providing wool clothing to keep them warm?
18Jb 31:21 "If I raised my hand against an orphan, knowing the judges would take my side,
18Jb 31:22 then let my shoulder be wrenched out of place! Let my arm be torn from its socket!
18Jb 31:23 That would be better than facing God's judgment.For if the majesty of God opposes me, what hope is there?
18Jb 31:24 "Have I put my trust in money or felt secure because of my gold?
18Jb 31:25 Have I gloated about my wealth and all that I own?
18Jb 31:26 "Have I looked at the sun shining in the skies, or the moon walking down its silver pathway,
18Jb 31:27 and been secretly enticed in my heart to throw kisses at them in worship?
18Jb 31:28 If so, I should be punished by the judges, for it would mean I had denied the God of heaven.
18Jb 31:29 "Have I ever rejoiced when disaster struck my enemies, or become excited when harm came their way?
18Jb 31:30 No, I have never sinned by cursing anyone or by asking for revenge.
18Jb 31:31 "My servants have never said, 'He let others go hungry.'
18Jb 31:32 I have never turned away a stranger but have opened my doors to everyone.
18Jb 31:33 "Have I tried to hide my sins like other people do, concealing my guilt in my heart?
18Jb 31:34 Have I feared the crowd or the contempt of the masses, so that I kept quiet and stayed indoors?
18Jb 31:35 "If only someone would listen to me! Look, I will sign my name to my defense. Let the Almighty answer me.Let my accuser write out the charges against me.
18Jb 31:36 I would face the accusation proudly.I would wear it like a crown.
18Jb 31:37 For I would tell him exactly what I have done.I would come before him like a prince.
18Jb 31:38 "If my land accuses me and all its furrows cry out together,
18Jb 31:39 or if I have stolen its crops or murdered its owners,
18Jb 31:40 then let thistles grow on that land instead of wheat, and weeds instead of barley." Job's words are ended.
18Jb 32:1 Job's three friends refused to reply further to him because he kept insisting on his innocence.
18Jb 32:2 Then Elihu son of Barakel the Buzite, of the clan of Ram, became angry. He was angry because Job refused to admit that he had sinned and that God was right in punishing him.
18Jb 32:3 He was also angry with Job's three friends, for they made God®Á appear to be wrong by their inability to answer Job's arguments. / ®ÁAs in ancient Hebrew scribal tradition; the Masoretic Text reads Job
18Jb 32:4 Elihu had waited for the others to speak to Job because they were older than he.
18Jb 32:5 But when he saw that they had no further reply, he spoke out angrily.
18Jb 32:6 Elihu son of Barakel the Buzite said, "I am young and you are old, so I held back from telling you what I think.
18Jb 32:7 I thought, 'Those who are older should speak, for wisdom comes with age.'
18Jb 32:8 But there is a spirit®Á within people, the breath of the Almighty within them, that makes them intelligent. / ®ÁOr Spirit; also in 32.18
18Jb 32:9 Sometimes the elders are not wise.Sometimes the aged do not understand justice.
18Jb 32:10 So listen to me, and let me tell you what I think.
18Jb 32:11 "I have waited all this time, listening very carefully to your arguments, listening to you grope for words.
18Jb 32:12 I have listened, but not one of you has refuted Job or answered his arguments.
18Jb 32:13 And don't tell me, 'He is too wise for us.Only God can convince him.'
18Jb 32:14 If Job had been arguing with me, I would not answer with your kind of logic!
18Jb 32:15 You sit there baffled, with nothing more to say.
18Jb 32:16 Should I continue to wait, now that you are silent? Must I also remain silent?
18Jb 32:17 No, I will say my piece.I will speak my mind.
18Jb 32:18 For I am full of pent-up words, and the spirit within me urges me on.
18Jb 32:19 I am like a cask of wine without a vent, like a new wineskin ready to burst!
18Jb 32:20 I must speak to find relief, so let me give my answers.
18Jb 32:21 I won't play favorites or try to flatter anyone.
18Jb 32:22 For if I tried flattery, my Creator would soon destroy me.
18Jb 33:1 "Listen to my words, Job; pay attention to what I have to say.
18Jb 33:2 Now that I have begun to speak, let me continue.
18Jb 33:3 I speak with all sincerity; I speak the truth.
18Jb 33:4 For the Spirit of God has made me, and the breath of the Almighty gives me life.
18Jb 33:5 Answer me, if you can; make your case and take your stand.
18Jb 33:6 Look, you and I both belong to God.I, too, was formed from clay.
18Jb 33:7 So you don't need to be afraid of me.I won't come down hard on you.
18Jb 33:8 "You have spoken in my hearing, and I have heard your very words.
18Jb 33:9 You said, 'I am pure; I am without sin; I am innocent; I have no guilt.
18Jb 33:10 God is picking a quarrel with me, and he considers me his enemy.
18Jb 33:11 He puts my feet in the stocks and watches my every move.'
18Jb 33:12 "But you are wrong, and I will show you why.For God is greater than any human being.
18Jb 33:13 So why are you bringing a charge against him? Why say he does not respond to people's complaints?
18Jb 33:14 For God speaks again and again, though people do not recognize it.
18Jb 33:15 He speaks in dreams, in visions of the night, when deep sleep falls on people as they lie in their beds.
18Jb 33:16 He whispers in their ears and terrifies them with warnings.
18Jb 33:17 He makes them turn from doing wrong; he keeps them from pride.
18Jb 33:18 He protects them from the grave, from crossing over the river of death.
18Jb 33:19 "Or God disciplines people with pain on their sickbeds, with ceaseless aching in their bones.
18Jb 33:20 They lose their appetite for even the most delicious food.
18Jb 33:21 Their flesh wastes away, and their bones stick out.
18Jb 33:22 They are at death's door; the angels of death wait for them.
18Jb 33:23 "But if an angel from heaven appears - a special messenger to intercede for a person and declare that he is upright - 
18Jb 33:24 he will be gracious and say,'Rescue him from the grave, for I have found a ransom for his life.'
18Jb 33:25 Then his body will become as healthy as a child's, firm and youthful again.
18Jb 33:26 When he prays to God, he will be accepted. And God will receive him with joy and restore him to good standing.
18Jb 33:27 He will declare to his friends,'I sinned and twisted the truth, but it was not worth it®Á. / ®ÁGreek version reads but he [God] did not punish me as my sin deserved
18Jb 33:28 God rescued me from the grave, and now my life is filled with light.'
18Jb 33:29 "Yes, God does these things again and again for people.
18Jb 33:30 He rescues them from the grave so they may enjoy the light of life.
18Jb 33:31 Mark this well, Job. Listen to me, for I have more to say.
18Jb 33:32 But if you have anything to say, go ahead.Speak, for I am anxious to see you justified.
18Jb 33:33 But if not, then listen to me.Keep silent and I will teach you wisdom!"
18Jb 34:1 Then Elihu said.
18Jb 34:2 "Listen to me, you wise men.Pay attention, you who have knowledge.
18Jb 34:3 Job said, 'The ear tests the words it hears just as the mouth distinguishes between foods.'
18Jb 34:4 So let us discern for ourselves what is right; let us learn together what is good.
18Jb 34:5 For Job also said, 'I am innocent, but God has taken away my rights.
18Jb 34:6 I am innocent, but they call me a liar.My suffering is incurable, though I have not sinned.'
18Jb 34:7 "Tell me, has there ever been a man like Job, with his thirst for irreverent talk?
18Jb 34:8 He chooses evil people as companions.He spends his time with wicked men.
18Jb 34:9 He has even said, 'Why waste time trying to please God?'
18Jb 34:10 "Listen to me, you who have understanding.Everyone knows that God doesn't sin! The Almighty can do no wrong.
18Jb 34:11 He repays people according to their deeds.He treats people as they deserve.
18Jb 34:12 Truly, God will not do wrong.The Almighty will not twist justice.
18Jb 34:13 Did someone else put the world in his care? Who set the whole world in place?
18Jb 34:14 If God were to take back his spirit and withdraw his breath,
18Jb 34:15 all life would cease, and humanity would turn again to dust.
18Jb 34:16 "Now listen to me if you are wise.Pay attention to what I say.
18Jb 34:17 Could God govern if he hated justice? Are you going to condemn the almighty judge?
18Jb 34:18 For he says to kings, 'You are wicked,' and to nobles, 'You are unjust.'
18Jb 34:19 He doesn't care how great a person may be, and he pays no more attention to the rich than to the poor.He made them all.
18Jb 34:20 In a moment they die.In the middle of the night they pass away; the mighty are removed without human hand.
18Jb 34:21 "For God watches how people live; he sees everything they do.
18Jb 34:22 No darkness is thick enough to hide the wicked from his eyes.
18Jb 34:23 We don't set the time when we will come before God in judgment.
18Jb 34:24 He brings the mighty to ruin without asking anyone, and he sets up others in their place.
18Jb 34:25 He knows what they do, and in the night he overturns and destroys them.
18Jb 34:26 He strikes them down because they are wicked, doing it openly for all to see.
18Jb 34:27 For they turned away from following him.They have no respect for any of his ways.
18Jb 34:28 They cause the poor to cry out, catching God's attention.He hears the cries of the needy.
18Jb 34:29 But if he chooses to remain quiet, who can criticize him? When he hides his face, no one can find him, whether an individual or a nation.
18Jb 34:30 He prevents the godless from ruling so they cannot be a snare to the people.
18Jb 34:31 "Why don't people say to God, 'I have sinned, but I will sin no more'?
18Jb 34:32 Or 'I don't know what evil I have done - tell me.If I have done wrong, I will stop at once'?
18Jb 34:33 "Must God tailor his justice to your demands? But you have rejected him! The choice is yours, not mine.Go ahead, share your wisdom with us.
18Jb 34:34 After all, bright people will tell me, and wise people will hear me say,
18Jb 34:35 'Job speaks out of ignorance; his words lack insight.'
18Jb 34:36 Job, you deserve the maximum penalty for the wicked way you have talked.
18Jb 34:37 For you have added rebellion to your sin; you show no respect, and you speak many angry words against God."
18Jb 35:1 Then Elihu said.
18Jb 35:2 "Do you think it is right for you to claim, 'I am righteous before God'?
18Jb 35:3 For you also ask, 'What's in it for me? What's the use of living a righteous life?'
18Jb 35:4 "I will answer you and all your friends, too.
18Jb 35:5 Look up into the sky, and see the clouds high above you.
18Jb 35:6 If you sin, how does that affect God? Even if you sin again and again, what effect will it have on him?
18Jb 35:7 If you are good, is this some great gift to him? What could you possibly give him?
18Jb 35:8 No, your sins affect only people like yourself, and your good deeds also affect only humans.
18Jb 35:9 "People cry out when they are oppressed.They groan beneath the power of the mighty.
18Jb 35:10 Yet they don't ask, 'Where is God my Creator, the one who gives songs in the night?
18Jb 35:11 Where is the one who makes us smarter than the animals and wiser than the birds of the sky?'
